## Assessing validity

For each of the following ten problems, use the table to determine whether the argument is valid or invalid. Then record your answer by answering the subsequent yes/no question appropriately.

*Example 1*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 a/\(b/\c) :|-: b/\c
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $a/\(b/\c)$ and premise $b/\c$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~



*Example 2*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 c/\(d/\e) :|-: e
~~~

Hence, is the argument with premise $c\wedge (d\wedge e)$ and conclusion $e$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~


*Example 3*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 ~e\/f :|-: ~e
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $\neg e$ and premise $\neg e\vee f$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| Yes
| *No
~~~


*Example 4*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 ~j,~z :|-: ~(j\/z)
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $\neg (j\vee z)$ and premises $\neg j$ and $\neg z$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~


*Example 5*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 (a\/b), (b\/c), ~b :|-: a/\c
~~~

Hence, is the argument with premises $a\vee b$ and $b\vee c$ and $\neg b$ and conclusion $a\wedge c$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~


*Example 6*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 r,t :|-: s\/(r/\t)
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $s\vee (r\wedge t)$ and premises $r$ and $t$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~

*Example 7*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 t\/s :|-: (t\/s)/\r
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $(t\/s)/\r$ and premise $t\/s$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| Yes
| *No
~~~

*Example 8*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 ~a, ~a->b :|-: b
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $b$ and premises $~a$ and $~a\rightarrow b$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| *Yes
| No
~~~

*Example 9*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 c, ~d->c :|-: ~d
~~~

Hence, is the argument with conclusion $\neg d$ and premises $c$ and $\neg d\rightarrow c$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| Yes
| *No
~~~

*Example 10*

~~~{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" options="nodash autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 u\/v, u->v :|-: u
~~~

Hence, is the argument with premises $u\vee v$ and $u\rightarrow v$ and conclusion $u$ a valid argument?

~~~{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}

| Yes
| *No
~~~

